He's certainly in some new scrape, said Emmerson to
himself. That a child may see. Poor fellow! It may
be a duel. I've a great mind to go after him. But he's too
far. I could overtake him. But, after all, why should I
put myself to trouble for him or any one else? I don't wish
to mingle myself with such matters. Besides, I've to see
Green about that new purchase at sevenand it only wants
ten minutes. He did not ask my advice! He's old enough
to take care of himself It's his affair! Every man for
himself in this world!
And so he turned his steps, not towards the theatre, where
he had no idea of going, but to Mr. Green's, to consult on
a promising speculation.
Frank had nearly reached the City Hotel, when he met
